'''Gustave Fougères''' (24 April 1863, [[Baume-les-Dames]] ([[Doubs]]) – 7 December 1927, Paris, aged 64) was a French [[archaeologist]], spécialist of [[archaic Greece]].
== Biography == A student of the [[École normale supérieure]], he joined the [[French School at Athens]] in 1885. He explored [[Thessaly]] and [[Anatolia]] and searched the gymnasium of [[Delos]] (1886) and the ancient city of [[Mantineia]] with its elliptical rampart (1887–1888).
He taught in Lille and Paris, traveling through Greece repeatedly and published his ''Guide de la Grèce''.
In 1913, after he became director of the French School at Athens, he continued the excavations already begun at Delos, [[Thasos]] and [[Philippi]] and opened new sites in [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]] and Anatolia ([[Claros]], [[Aphrodisias]]). Archaeological research in Greece were interrupted by First World War.
He taught archaeology at the [[Sorbonne]] from 1919. His courses attracted many foreign students.<ref>[http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/bch_0007-4217_1928_num_52_1_2913 Gustave Fougères (1863–1927)], {{Interlanguage link multi|Bulletin de correspondance hellénique|fr}}, 1928, vol. 52</ref><ref>[http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/rbph_0035-0818_1928_num_7_1_6505 Gustave Fougères], ''Bulletin de correspondance hellénique'', obituary, 1928, vol. 7, (p.&nbsp;394–395)</ref>
== Selected publications == *1898: ''Mantinée et l'Arcadie Orientale'' *1910: ''Sélinonte'' *1911: [https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008916326 ''Guide de la Grèce''], Guides Joanne, 2<sup>e</sup> edition *1912: [https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/101711348 ''Athènes]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review of ''Athènes'' by Gustave Fougères|journal=The Athenaeum|issue=No. 4458|date=5 April 1913|pages=378–379|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$c108351;view=1up;seq=280}}</ref>
