'''Pancake sentences''' are a phenomenon in [[Scandinavia]]n [[linguistics]] where [[Agreement (linguistics)|sentence agreement]] does not follow conventional linguistic patterns. The phrase appears to have been [[Neologism|coined]] by [[Hans-Olav Enger]] in a 2004 academic paper, "Scandinavian pancake sentences as semantic agreement" but it was well-known also by classic grammar and was dubbed "constructio ad sensum" or "syllepsis"; see [[zeugma and syllepsis]]. Enger states that pancake sentences are "where the predicative adjective apparently disagrees with its subject". This phenomenon may be related or compared to English language linguistics, where [[American English]] speakers might say "the team <u>has</u> arrived", [[syntax|syntactically]] agreeing the singular ''team'', versus [[British English]] speakers saying "the team <u>have</u> arrived", agreeing [[semantics|semantically]] to the collective noun ''team''.

An example from Swedish is the sentence "''Pannkakor är nyttigt''":

:{| 
|-
| ''Pannkak-or'' || ''är'' || ''nyttig-t''
|-
| Pancake-{{small|C.PL}} || {{small|COP}} || healthy-{{small|NEUT.SG}} 
|-
|colspan=9|It’s healthy to have pancakes.
|}

While ''Pannkakor'' 'pancakes' is plural and of common gender, ''nyttigt'' 'healthy' is inflected to singular and neuter.

A similar phenomenon also occurs in [[Modern Hebrew|Hebrew]], where the copula (and adjectives) appear to disagree with the subject, as well as is [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] with some nouns used without the article (''Água é bom. É proibido entrada. Está proibido brincadeiras. '') when feminine nouns of either number agree with a masculine adjective in its singular form.

